{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"[G3 child-coverage — container review of parent 1f19-adf2-ffb2-4b09 paired with THIS child (S5 b7fa: Surface the ref + source controls on the CLI and MCP tool schemas)]\n\n4-bucket audit of this child's contribution to the parent's acceptance/success criteria; every absence cross-checked against the WHOLE 8-child roster (S1 6d56 materialize core, S2 70c7 cache+janitor, S2b b73c janitor reclamation, S3 fa49 gate threading, S4 30b3 attested signing, S4b e308 claim-gate↔plan-review coherence + ADR 0002, S6 1ba5 docs). The union of children covers every parent criterion; no uncovered parent criterion. EMPTY G3 findings list.\n\nCoverage map (parent AC -> covering child/children; this child's role):\n- Parent AC1 (no code-reading gate reads the server's working tree in attested mode; all read a faithful snapshot materialized at the pinned SHA) — FULLY by S1 (materialize core) + S3 (gate re-rooting). This child SURFACES ref/source and its AC5 proves the cwd/branch decoupling (verified-code path does not depend on the MCP server's checked-out branch; REBAR_ROOT only locates the object DB). STRUCTURAL/surface w.r.t. this child; underlying behavior scoped out (\"Out: the underlying behavior (S1-S4)\"). Not an absence.\n- Parent AC2 (signed verdict binds verified_at_sha via the signed manifest channel — no payload-schema/version change, prior signatures still verify — and is reproducible against that SHA) — FULLY by S4 (30b3 manifest-channel SHA binding) atop S1's immutable-SHA basis. This child is the SURFACE owner of the verified_at_sha EXPOSURE: its AC3 (attested results surface verified_at_sha) + AC2 (omitting --ref resolves origin/main->SHA in attested and still signs, pin recorded). The manifest-channel/no-payload-bump mechanics are S4's. Not an absence.\n- Parent AC3 (local reads in-place checkout AND cannot produce a signed verdict; documented back-out restoring prior in-place behavior) — by S3 (in-place read) + S4 (signing bar) + S6 (documents the back-out). This child makes --source=local REACHABLE from BOTH surfaces and reflects it as unsigned (its AC2/AC4). Surface contribution; behavior/enforcement owned by S3/S4, prose by S6. Not an absence.\n- Parent AC4 (concurrent gates on same/different SHAs without git-lock contention or cross-op corruption; cache + janitor reclaim disk under a defined free-space watermark without disrupting in-flight reads) — FULLY by S1 (atomic population) + S2 (single-flight, reader-safety) + S2b (janitor reclamation under disk pressure). STRUCTURAL w.r.t. this child (scoped out: \"Out: the underlying behavior (S1-S4)\"). Not an absence.\n- Parent AC5 (private-repo fetch failure surfaces a descriptive, actionable credential error) — FULLY by S1 (raises) + S6 (documents message+remedy). This child owns the COMPLEMENTARY surface-level validation/failure paths (its AC4: unresolvable/absent ref, invalid --source, unreachable object DB at REBAR_ROOT each fail closed with an actionable error — covered by tests, cf. S1). The credential-error facet itself = S1+S6. Not an absence.\n- Parent AC6 (portable across macOS + Linux: no external tar; no hardcoded /tmp; flock+mkdir fallback) — FULLY by S1 (implementation) + S6 (docs). STRUCTURAL w.r.t. this child. Not an absence.\n- Parent AC7 (operational tunables — free-space watermark, default ref, grace/age windows — configurable with documented defaults, S2/S3) — FULLY by S2/S2b (watermark, grace/age) + S3 (default ref/source via standard config precedence). This child SURFACES the --ref/--source documented defaults at the schema layer (its AC1: documented defaults; AC last-block: --source defaults attested, --ref origin/main). Surface contribution; the config mechanism is S2/S3. Not an absence.\n- Parent AC8 (an ADR captures the architecture + rejected alternatives — PID-lease, payload-schema SHA binding) — FULLY by S2/S4 (authored) + S4b (ADR 0002 coherence). This child records the cwd/branch decoupling + CLI<->MCP mapping IN the ADR (its final AC), a surface contribution to the same ADR. Not an absence.\n- Parent AC9 (all EIGHT enumerated child stories closed; make lint + full test suite green) — STRUCTURAL/meta epic-completion criterion; the roster contains exactly the eight enumerated children (S1 6d56, S2 70c7, S2b b73c, S3 fa49, S4 30b3, S4b e308, S5 b7fa, S6 1ba5) — this child is one of the eight, with its own green-bar obligation (covered-by-named-set). Not an absence.\n\nSuccess-criteria narrative (\"every code-reading gate verifies a CLIENT-SPECIFIED, immutable, reproducible snapshot at a pinned SHA — never the server's mutable checkout — safely under concurrent distributed use; signed verdicts bind verified_at_sha via the manifest channel (reproducible, no prior-signature breakage); local mode preserves the single-developer verify-before-push workflow\") decomposes onto AC1-AC3. The \"CLIENT-SPECIFIED\" clause is precisely this child's core deliverable: surfacing --ref/ref + --source/source on BOTH the CLI and the five MCP tool schemas (review_plan/verify_completion/review_ticket/review_code/scan_spec) with a pinned one-to-one CLI<->MCP mapping and origin/main defaults (its AC1/AC2/AC6 vertical slice) is what makes the snapshot client-targetable. verified_at_sha exposure = its AC3; unsigned-local reflection = its AC2/AC4. No uncovered obligation introduced.\n\nDelegation cross-checks (covered-by-named-consumer, not absences): this child's Scope explicitly delegates \"the underlying behavior (S1-S4)\" and \"prose docs (S6)\" — each claimed by a named sibling (materialization S1; cache/janitor S2/S2b; gate threading S3; manifest-channel signing S4; ADR-0002 coherence S4b; ref/source-semantics prose S6 AC3). The machine-facing schema-text defaults are this child's own; human prose is S6 — clean schema-text-vs-prose split, each artifact claimed once.\n\nCoverage-pairing note (clean for G3): S5 and S3 (fa49) both name ref+source on the SAME five operations — producer/surface split (S3 threads the params into the gate dispatch and re-roots file tools; S5 exposes them on the CLI/MCP schema with the pinned one-to-one mapping and documented defaults). Each scoped out of the other (S5: \"Out: the underlying behavior (S1-S4)\"; S3: \"Out: ... CLI/MCP surface schemas (S5)\"). No double-ownership and no union-coverage gap; this child's AC1 one-to-one mapping closes the naming-drift risk. (The standing base/head+--diff-file code-review SURFACE-retirement seam between S3 and S5 is a G4 consistency concern about WHO retires the legacy surface controls, not a G3 union-coverage gap — the single-ref code-review obligation is CLAIMED by a child, S3 AC3.)\n\nConclusion: this child cleanly covers the CLI/MCP surfacing slice (--ref/ref + --source/source on all five CLI commands AND their MCP counterparts with documented defaults + one-to-one mapping; origin/main still signs; local reachable+reflected-unsigned from both surfaces; verified_at_sha surfaced; surface-level validation/failure paths fail closed; cwd/branch decoupling proven; ADR records the mapping; vertical-slice-first sequencing) — it is the surface primary owner of the \"client-specified\" success-criteria clause and the verified_at_sha exposure half of AC2. No parent acceptance/success criterion is left uncovered by the roster. No G3 finding for this pairing."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782532270029338001,"uuid":"826ed9ed-5ee7-4e5c-8682-1887a0aacbf4"}